item.description:
A name sometimes means the composite substance, or the actuality or form.
e.g. whether &lsquo;house&rsquo; is a sign for the composite thing, &lsquo;a covering consisting of bricks and stones laid thus and thus&rsquo;, or for the actuality or form, &lsquo;a covering&rsquo;, and whether a line is &rsquo;twoness in length&rsquo; or &rsquo;twoness&rsquo;, and whether an animal is soul in a body&rsquo; or &lsquo;a soul&rsquo;;
for soul is the substance or actuality of some body.
